.TH PWLDAPD 8 "March 2026" "pwldapd" "System Administration"
.
.SH NAME
pwldapd \- LDAP daemon backed by the local POSIX user and group database
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pwldapd
.RB [ \-l
.IR addr ]
.RB [ \-\-tls\-listen
.IR addr ]
.RB [ \-b
.IR dn ]
.RB [ \-u
.IR range ]
.RB [ \-g
.IR range ]
.RB [ \-\-tls\-cert
.IR file ]
.RB [ \-\-tls\-key
.IR file ]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B pwldapd
is a read-only LDAP server (RFC\ 4510) that exposes the local POSIX user
and group database over the LDAP protocol.
It reads accounts through the system's name-service switch (NSS) layer
and presents them as a standard
.BR posixAccount / inetOrgPerson
and
.B posixGroup
directory tree.
Bind requests are authenticated via PAM.
Anonymous binds are accepted.
.PP
The daemon is intended for use on a single host where LDAP-aware
applications\(emsuch as SSH, sudo, or web servers\(emneed to look up
local accounts without requiring a separate directory service.
It does not persist any state and does not support write operations.
.
.SS Directory structure
The served tree is rooted at the base DN (see
.BR \-\-base\-dn )
and has the following layout:
.PP
.RS
.nf
dc=host,dc=example,dc=com
\(lc\(em ou=people
\(lc   \(lc\(em uid=alice,...
\(lc   \(aq\(em uid=bob,...
\(aq\(em ou=groups
    \(lc\(em cn=staff,...
    \(aq\(em cn=wheel,...
.fi
.RE
.PP
Each
.B uid=\c
\fIname\fR
entry under
.B ou=people
carries the following attributes:
.BR objectClass " (top, posixAccount, inetOrgPerson),"
.BR uid ,
.BR cn ,
.BR sn ,
.BR givenName ,
.BR uidNumber ,
.BR gidNumber ,
.BR homeDirectory ,
.BR loginShell ,
.BR gecos .
The
.BR givenName ,
.BR roomNumber ,
.BR telephoneNumber ,
and
.B homePhone
attributes are also populated when the corresponding GECOS fields
are non-empty (see
.BR GECOS\ PARSING ).
.PP
Each
.B cn=\c
\fIname\fR
entry under
.B ou=groups
carries:
.BR objectClass " (top, posixGroup),"
.BR cn ,
.BR gidNumber ,
.BR memberUid .
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-l " addr" ", \-\-listen=" addr
Plain (non-TLS) address and port to listen on.
May be specified more than once to listen on multiple addresses.
IPv6 addresses must use bracket notation (see
.BR IPv6 ).
Default:
.BR 127.0.0.1:389 .
.TP
.BI \-\-tls\-listen= addr
TLS address and port to listen on.
May be specified more than once.
Requires
.B \-\-tls\-cert
and
.BR \-\-tls\-key .
.TP
.BI \-b " dn" ", \-\-base\-dn=" dn
LDAP base DN, for example
.BR dc=example,dc=com .
If omitted,
.B pwldapd
derives the base DN from the system's fully-qualified hostname (see
.BR "BASE DN DERIVATION" ).
.TP
.BI \-u " range" ", \-\-uid\-range=" range
Restrict served user accounts to this UID range.
.I range
is either a single UID
.RI ( N )
or an inclusive range
.RI ( N\-M ).
May be repeated to allow multiple disjoint ranges.
Default:
.BR 1000\-65535 .
.TP
.BI \-g " range" ", \-\-gid\-range=" range
Restrict served groups to this GID range.
.I range
follows the same format as
.BR \-\-uid\-range .
May be repeated.
If omitted, all groups are served.
The primary group of every served user is always included regardless of
this setting, so that
.B gidNumber
in user entries always resolves to a visible group.
.TP
.BI \-\-tls\-cert= file
Path to a PEM-encoded TLS certificate (or certificate chain).
Must be given together with
.BR \-\-tls\-key .
.TP
.BI \-\-tls\-key= file
Path to a PEM-encoded TLS private key.
Must be given together with
.BR \-\-tls\-cert .
.
.SH BASE DN DERIVATION
When
.B \-\-base\-dn
is not specified,
.B pwldapd
derives the base DN from the system hostname:
.IP 1. 4
Call
.BR gethostname (2)
to obtain the local hostname.
.IP 2. 4
If the hostname contains at least one dot and the domain portion is not
.B local
or
.BR localdomain ,
convert the full hostname to a base DN by splitting on dots and
prepending each component with
.BR dc= .
For example,
.B server.example.com
becomes
.BR dc=server,dc=example,dc=com .
.IP 3. 4
If the hostname is unqualified (no dot), attempt a DNS canonical-name
lookup via
.BR getaddrinfo (3)
with
.B AI_CANONNAME
and repeat step\ 2 with the returned FQDN.
.PP
If the base DN cannot be determined,
.B pwldapd
exits with an error and the operator must supply
.BR \-\-base\-dn .
.
.SH IPv6
IPv6 addresses must be enclosed in square brackets:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd \-\-listen [::1]:389
pwldapd \-\-listen [::]:389
.fi
.RE
.
.SH TLS (LDAPS)
.B pwldapd
supports TLS via the LDAPS convention (a separate port, typically 636,
where TLS is negotiated immediately upon connection).
StartTLS is not supported.
.PP
To enable TLS, supply both
.B \-\-tls\-cert
and
.B \-\-tls\-key
together with one or more
.B \-\-tls\-listen
addresses:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd \-\-tls\-listen [::]:636 \e
        \-\-tls\-cert /etc/ssl/certs/ldap.pem \e
        \-\-tls\-key  /etc/ssl/private/ldap.key
.fi
.RE
.PP
Plain and TLS listeners can coexist:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd \-\-listen 127.0.0.1:389 \e
        \-\-tls\-listen [::]:636  \e
        \-\-tls\-cert /etc/ssl/certs/ldap.pem \e
        \-\-tls\-key  /etc/ssl/private/ldap.key
.fi
.RE
.
.SH PAM CONFIGURATION
.B pwldapd
authenticates bind requests via PAM using the service name
.BR pwldapd .
The file
.B /etc/pam.d/pwldapd
must exist before any authenticated bind is attempted; without it PAM
falls back to
.BR /etc/pam.d/other ,
which on most systems denies all access.
.PP
A minimal configuration delegating to the standard system auth stack:
.PP
.RS
.nf
auth     required   pam_unix.so
account  required   pam_unix.so
.fi
.RE
.PP
On systems that use the include-based layout:
.PP
.RS
.nf
@include common-auth
@include common-account
.fi
.RE
.PP
Using a dedicated PAM service allows LDAP-specific policies such as
per-service failure delays, audit logging, or restricting which accounts
may bind via LDAP.
.
.SH GECOS PARSING
The GECOS field is interpreted as up to five comma-separated values in the
traditional BSD format:
.PP
.RS
.I "Full Name,Room Number,Work Phone,Home Phone,Other"
.RE
.PP
The full name becomes the
.BR cn ,
.BR sn ,
and (when two or more words are present)
.B givenName
attributes.
.BR roomNumber ,
.BR telephoneNumber ,
and
.B homePhone
are set from fields 1, 2, and 3 respectively when non-empty.
The fifth field has no standard LDAP mapping and is ignored.
.
.SH LISTENING ON PORT 389
Port 389 requires elevated privileges.
The recommended approach is to grant the binary the
.B CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE
capability rather than running as root:
.PP
.RS
.nf
sudo setcap cap_net_bind_service=ep /usr/local/sbin/pwldapd
.fi
.RE
.PP
Alternatively, configure a firewall redirect from a high port:
.PP
.RS
.nf
iptables \-t nat \-A PREROUTING \-p tcp \-\-dport 389 \e
    \-j REDIRECT \-\-to\-port 3389
.fi
.RE
.PP
Or use a service manager that provides socket activation.
.
.SH LOGGING
Log verbosity is controlled by the
.B RUST_LOG
environment variable.
The default level is
.BR info ,
which logs listener startup, each new connection, and all bind outcomes.
.PP
To enable debug logging for
.B pwldapd
only:
.PP
.RS
.nf
RUST_LOG=pwldapd=debug pwldapd
.fi
.RE
.PP
To enable debug logging for all crates:
.PP
.RS
.nf
RUST_LOG=debug pwldapd
.fi
.RE
.
.SH LIMITATIONS
.B pwldapd
is intentionally a read-only LDAP front-end.
The following features are not supported:
.IP \(bu 4
Write operations (Add, Delete, Modify, ModifyDN).
.IP \(bu 4
SASL authentication.
.IP \(bu 4
StartTLS (use a dedicated LDAPS port instead).
.IP \(bu 4
Referrals or server-side sorting.
.IP \(bu 4
Persistent searches or change notifications.
.IP \(bu 4
Server-enforced size limits or time limits (client-requested values are
accepted on the wire but ignored).
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B RUST_LOG
Controls log verbosity.
See
.BR LOGGING .
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/pam.d/pwldapd
PAM service configuration for bind authentication.
Must be created before starting the daemon.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
Serve local users on the loopback with default settings:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd
.fi
.RE
.PP
Serve on all interfaces with a custom base DN and UID range:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd \-\-listen [::]:389 \e
        \-\-base\-dn dc=corp,dc=example,dc=com \e
        \-\-uid\-range 2000\-9999
.fi
.RE
.PP
LDAPS only, accepting connections from the network:
.PP
.RS
.nf
pwldapd \-\-listen "" \e
        \-\-tls\-listen [::]:636 \e
        \-\-tls\-cert /etc/ssl/certs/ldap.pem \e
        \-\-tls\-key  /etc/ssl/private/ldap.key
.fi
.RE
.PP
Point an NSS/LDAP client at a running instance:
.PP
.RS
.nf
uri     ldap://127.0.0.1/
base    dc=host,dc=example,dc=com
.fi
.RE
(Replace the base DN with whatever
.B pwldapd
logs at startup.)
.
